<TEI.2><text><body><div1 type="alphabetic letter" n="D" org="uniform" sample="complete"><entryFree key="Drudge" type="main" opt="n"><orth extent="full" opt="n">Drudge,</orth> subst. one employed in mean service, a slave: <cit><quote>he is contented thy poor d. to be,</quote> <bibl n="shak. son 151.11" default="NO" valid="yes">Sonn. 151, 11</bibl></cit>. <bibl n="shak. mv 3.2.103" default="NO" valid="yes">Merch. III, 2, 103</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. aww 1.3.49" default="NO" valid="yes">All's I, 3, 49</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. rom 2.5.77" default="NO" valid="yes">Rom. II, 5, 77</bibl> (fem.). Used as a term of reproach: <bibl n="shak. err 3.2.144" default="NO" valid="yes">Err. III, 2, 144</bibl> (fem.). <bibl n="shak. shr 4.1.132" default="NO" valid="yes">Shr. IV, 1, 132</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. 2h6 4.1.105" default="NO" valid="yes">H6B IV, 1, 105</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. 2h6 4.2.159" default="NO" valid="yes">IV, 2, 159</bibl>. <cit><quote>a very d. of nature's,</quote> <bibl n="shak. cym 5.2.5" default="NO" valid="yes">Cymb. V, 2, 5</bibl></cit> (cf. <cit><quote>the slave of nature,</quote> <bibl n="shak. r3 1.3.230" default="NO" valid="yes">R3 I, 3, 230</bibl></cit>, i. e. born for baseness).
</entryFree></div1></body></text></TEI.2>